		 	<span id="comment_score_64563651" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64563651); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~jenningsthecat">jenningsthecat</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~jenningsthecat">( 1525947 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64563651"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64563651"><p>Thanks - I was aware that methane is a much more powerful greenhouse gas than CO2, but I hadn't realized until you brought it up, and I looked it up, that its half-life is more than ten times shorter. So just cutting methane emissions could have a significant short-term benefit.</p><p>And tackling the methane problem might be easier, cheaper, and less controversial. We still need to drastically cut CO2 emissions, but at this point I'd be happy to see any kind of significant greenhouse gas reductions.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64563651">

